</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="27CF83EEF108346BFAA3A04AF1EAFCBB" box="[1293,1435,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="artibatum">
<emphasis id="D2BB247FF108346BFAA3A04AF1EAFCBB" box="[1293,1435,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">A. artibatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="78F4E4E8F108346BFF31A069F487FC66" box="[159,246,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 23" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1851]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 23. Allometopon atribatum spec. nov., holotype; 19: photo, dorsal; 20: photo, lateral; 21: external genitalia, left lateral; 22: same, posterior; 23: internal genitalia, left lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258770/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Fig. 
<number id="5607EA4AF108346BFF76A066F487FC66" box="[216,246,872,896]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
), especially the dark frons and the highly characteristic shape of the surstylus and basiphallus. These species are differentiated in the key.
</paragraph>
